  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A function <m>f:\B \to \C</m> is said to be
        <em>left cancelative</em> if,
        for all sets <m>\A</m> and all functions <m>g,h:\A \to \B</m>,
        <me>
          f \circ g = f \circ h \ \mbox{ implies }  \ \  g = h
        </me>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Show that <m>f</m> is left cancelative if and only if <m>f</m> is one-to-one.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A function <m>f:\B \to \C</m> is said to be
        <em>right cancelative</em> if,
        for all sets <m>\D</m> and all functions <m>g,h:\C \to \D</m>,
        <me>
          g \circ f = h \circ f, \ \ \mbox{ implies }  \ \ g = h
        </me>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Show that <m>f</m> is right cancelative if and only if <m>f</m> is onto <m>\C</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>
